vectorData.altText: The denticulate      ligaments are extensions of the pia mater that anchor the spinal cord bilaterally to the inner surface of the dural sac, thereby stabilizing the spinal cord.

The spinal cord, covered in pia mater, lies within the dural sac     in the sub    arachnoid space. In life, the subarachnoid space is filled with cerebrospinal fluid (CSF), the fluid that bathes the brain and spinal cord.
The plane between the dura and arachnoid, unlike the subarachnoid space, is a potential space. This means that in life, the arachnoid is held against the dura by the hydrostatic pressure of the CSF in the subarachnoid space.
remember, it is composed of dura and arachnoid
IDENTIFY the denticulate ligaments in your specimen.
They will appear as saw-tooth-shaped extensions from the lateral aspect of the cord.
Because the subarachnoid space was opened in the preparation of your specimen, the CSF drained out and the arachnoid has fallen away from the dura and onto the spinal cord.
